The foregoing and other objects, aspects and advantages will be better understood from the following detailed description of a preferred embodiment of the invention with reference to the drawings, in which:


FIG. 1 is a flow diagram showing the steps required for rapid liquid crystal filling of a display panel;


FIG. 2 shows in schematic form the inventive device with one liquid crystal panel to be filled;


FIG. 3 shows in schematic form the invention with a rack which can process multiple liquid crystal displays simultaneously; and


FIGS. 4A and 4B show in schematic form front and side views of an embodiment using thin strips of material attached to the panel sides to assure outward flexing during edge compression;


FIG. 5 is a side schematic view of a preferred embodiment of the invention which reduces pressure on the top sealed edge of a panel;


FIG. 6 is a side schematic view of a preferred embodiment of the invention which reduces pressure on the top sealed edge of a panel by directing a compression force at an angle away from the top or totally sealed edge;


FIG. 7 is a side schematic view of another embodiment of the invention;


FIG. 8 is a diagram illustrating the relationship between the channel flow rate and the channel width;


FIG. 9 is a schematic diagram of single glass plate having a beveled edge;


FIG. 10 is cross sectional view of panel having beveled edges being filled with a pipette; and


FIG. 11 is cross sectional view of panel having step edges being filled with a pipette.
